    "narrative_summary": "The TP53 c.666G>A (p.Pro222=) variant is a synonymous change in the DNA\u2011binding domain of the tumor\u2011suppressor gene TP53. It has been reported in the context of Li\u2011Fraumeni syndrome, breast\u2011cancer predisposition, lung cancer, and sporadic tumors such as chordoma and osteosarcoma.\nClinical data consistently describe the alteration as non\u2011pathogenic. In an Iranian lung\u2011cancer cohort the variant was classified as a novel benign change and its minor\u2011allele frequency was 6.7\u202f\u00d7\u202f10\u207b\u2075 [PMC6061986]. A ClinVar submission lists the variant as \u201clikely benign\u201d based on multiple submitters and provided criteria [PMC6672031]. A large Japanese case\u2011control study of breast\u2011cancer patients also records the variant as benign in its variant table [PMC6172276]. Additional reports of the variant in Lynch\u2011syndrome patients and in a colorectal\u2011lesion predictor cohort note its presence but do not assign pathogenicity [PMC5303590; PMC7899856].\nFunctional evidence is limited. One supplementary analysis of termination\u2011codon evolution notes that the c.666G>A change would generate a premature TGA stop codon (p.W222*), but this observation is presented as a bioinformatic illustration rather than an experimentally validated functional effect [PMC10471768]. No experimental assays demonstrating loss of TP53 function have been reported.\nPopulation data are sparse but consistent with a rare, likely neutral allele. The Iranian study reports a low allele frequency (\u22486.7\u202f\u00d7\u202f10\u207b\u2075) and the Japanese cohort classifies the variant as benign without providing a specific frequency, supporting its rarity in the general population.\nOverall, the preponderance of clinical classifications (benign or likely benign) and the absence of functional data indicating deleterious impact lead to the conclusion that TP53 c.666G>A is a benign synonymous variant. The isolated bioinformatic claim of a stop\u2011codon creation does not outweigh the weight of clinical evidence, and the variant is best interpreted as non\u2011pathogenic in the contexts examined.",
